When to buy and when to sell: an analysis of the video game market¶

Introduction¶

Video games have been growing in popularity in recent years, and, as demand for them increases, so too does their prices. As a collector, I spend a lot of time tracking prices, trying to find the right time to buy and the right time to sell. In this tutorial, my aim is to analyze data collected on the prices of games to see if I can create a model that accurately predicts the ideal time to sell a game based on desired price and genre. Automating this process will help me learn when to prioritize certain games for my collection and reduce the amount of manual tracking I do from day to day.

Resources¶

Throughout the project, various packages were used. To get a better understanding of their functionality, you can read their official documentation, linked here:

pandas, used for data management: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/

sklearn.model_selection, used for testing and selecting models: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/classes.html#module-sklearn.model_selection

Data Collection¶

Before we can analyze data, we have to collect it. To begin this step of the process, I utilized pricecharting.com, a trusted data aggregate site in the collecting scene that tracks the average sale price of video games, trading cards and comic books across multiple storefronts. From this site, I downloaded a CSV at https://www.pricecharting.com/download-price-guide/c650d0044789fbba6e5ca58946c82f1a12a5d0e2 which contained a database of nearly 75,000 entries with the console name, the product name, the price loose, or with no box, the price in box with all inserts, i.e. advertisements and manuals, the price factory sealed, the genre and the release date. The data used in this notebook is representative of the price data as of May 10th, 2022.

After May 10th, the data used expired. So, for the sake of reproducibility, the exact data used has been uploaded at https://github.com/cam-wit/game-sale-data-may10-2022

Data management/representation¶

The first step I'll be taking to clean up this data is to filter it by console name. The provided CSV includes some non-video game consoles, such as Amiibo and Disney Infinity, which are game-adjacent toy lines. It also includes listings for the same console from different regions, i.e. JP, short for Japan, and PAL, short for Phase Alternate Line, a video format standard primarily used throughout Europe. As I am primarily interested in analyzing the American game collecting scene, I don't need the data for non-video games or different regions in my dataset to perform the relevant analysis.

The same cannot be done for NaN entries in the price columns. An NaN in any price column directly indicates that no sales of the current game in the specified conditions were found. This can indicate a few different things.

More likely than not, it indicates a lack of demand. However, it could also indicate a lack of supply. If there's a lack of demand, it would suggest that, were you to sell that game, it would sell for a little. But, in certain situations, where there's lack of demand, it could be worth a lot of money.

To deal with this, I'll be using various forms of data imputation.

But, before we can do that, I first need to convert the various price data from strings to float representations of dollars so I can use mathematical operations on it.

# Iterate through each row in the dataframe
for index, row in data.iterrows():
    # For each price column, if data is present, convert it from a string to a float value representing dollar amount
    if not pd.isna(row['loose-price']):
        data.at[index, 'loose-price'] = float(row['loose-price'][1:])
    if not pd.isna(row['cib-price']):
        data.at[index, 'cib-price'] = float(row['cib-price'][1:])
    if not pd.isna(row['new-price']):
        data.at[index, 'new-price'] = float(row['new-price'][1:])

We can now impute the missing data.

In cases where there are no known prices for the price in any condition, I will drop the row from the dataframe. We won't have enough data necessary to conclude whether supply or demand is the problem. It is random whether or not the price would skew rise or lower the average. Therefore, dropping the rows should not have too much of an effect on the data present.

In cases where there is 1 known price and 2 unknown prices, I will include prices that have the same value proportional to their column mean as the known column value. A high value in one column generally suggests a high value in the others, and vice versa, so this should add values that appropriately take both condition and supply/demand into account.

Based on the same logic I just discussed, in cases where there are 2 known prices and 1 unknown price, I will include a price in the missing column that is has a proportion with the column's mean value equivalent to the 2 known column's mean proportion to their column means.

In [11]:
# Find the mean prices for loose games, complete-in-box games and new games
mean_loose = data['loose-price'].mean()
mean_cib = data['cib-price'].mean()
mean_new = data['new-price'].mean()

# Iterate through every row in the dataframe
for index, row in data.iterrows():
    # If no price data is known, drop the row.
    if pd.isna(row['loose-price']) and pd.isna(row['cib-price']) and pd.isna(row['new-price']):
        data = data.drop(index)
    # If 2 columns have their price data known, add the proportionally appropriate data to the unknown column
    elif pd.isna(row['loose-price']) and not pd.isna(row['cib-price']) and not pd.isna(row['new-price']):
        data.at[index, 'loose-price'] = mean_loose * ((row['cib-price']/mean_cib + row['new-price']/mean_new) / 2)
    elif not pd.isna(row['loose-price']) and pd.isna(row['cib-price']) and not pd.isna(row['new-price']):
        data.at[index, 'cib-price'] = mean_cib * ((row['loose-price']/mean_loose + row['new-price']/mean_new) / 2)
    elif not pd.isna(row['loose-price']) and not pd.isna(row['cib-price']) and pd.isna(row['new-price']):
        data.at[index, 'new-price'] = mean_new * ((row['cib-price']/mean_cib + row['loose-price']/mean_loose) / 2)
    # If 1 column has known price data, add the proportionally appropriate data to both unknown columns
    elif pd.isna(row['loose-price']) and pd.isna(row['cib-price']) and not pd.isna(row['new-price']):
        data.at[index, 'loose-price'] = mean_loose * (row['new-price']/mean_new)
        data.at[index, 'cib-price'] = mean_cib * (row['new-price']/mean_new)
    elif pd.isna(row['loose-price']) and not pd.isna(row['cib-price']) and pd.isna(row['new-price']):
        data.at[index, 'loose-price'] = mean_loose * (row['cib-price']/mean_cib)
        data.at[index, 'new-price'] = mean_new * (row['cib-price']/mean_cib)
    elif not pd.isna(row['loose-price']) and pd.isna(row['cib-price']) and pd.isna(row['new-price']):
        data.at[index, 'new-price'] = mean_new * (row['loose-price']/mean_loose)
        data.at[index, 'cib-price'] = mean_cib * (row['loose-price']/mean_loose)
        
# Display the data to ensure everything went as expected       
data

Before we can get the age, however, I'll first need to convert the release-date columns to datetime objects instead of strings so I can easily calculate the amount of days that have passed since its release.

Now that we have some data, we can move on to testing some hypotheses

Hypothesis testing¶

I suspect that the rarer a genre, or the less listings of it there are, the more valuable a game in it will be.

I will plot average price per genre against count of games per genre to further investigate.

In [25]:
# Import the necessary package
import numpy as np

# Get a list of the counts of each game per genre
gb = data.groupby('genre')
counts = [gb.get_group(x).size for x in gb.groups]

# Increase the figure sizze so every datapoint label is clearly visible despite the high concentration in the bottom left
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (20, 50)

# Label the graph and scatter the points
plt.figure()
plt.xlabel("Count of Games")
plt.ylabel("Average Price")
plt.title("Average Price vs. Count for Video Games")
plt.scatter(counts, avg_price_all)
# Label each scattered point
for i,label in enumerate(gb.groups.keys()):
    plt.text(counts[i], avg_price_all[i],label)
# Calculate m and b for the regression line and plot that line
m, b = np.polyfit(np.array(counts), np.array(avg_price_all), 1)
plt.plot(counts, m * np.array(avg_price_all) + b)
Out[25]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7faa86fbad60>]

This graph suggests that my theory is probably incorrect. The regression line does not fit the data very well, and we can observe that relatively unvaluable genres such as dance have lower counts than relatively valuable genres such as shoot 'em ups. Still, I will move forward with hypothesis testing.

The null hypothesis will be that there is no correlation between amount of games per genre and value.

The alternative hypothesis will be that there is a correlation.

A Pearson's correlation test will be performed to get the p-value and see if we can reject the null hypothesis.

In [26]:
# Import the necessary package
from scipy.stats import pearsonr

# Calculate the p-value for testing if there is a correlation between counts and price, and display it
stat, p = pearsonr(counts, avg_price_all)
p
Out[26]:
0.6345896162127201

This p-value is very high, so there is no evidence that we should reject the null hypothesis. We can therefore conclude that, based on this data, there does not seem to be a correlation between the amount of games in a genre and the value of games in a genre. I now know that I should not priority genre scarcity in building up my collection.

I'd also like to explore the hypothesis that Neo-Geo titles are particularly valuable. The null hypothesis is that games for the Neo-Geo AES are worth about the same as any game, while the alternative hypothesis is that they are not.

3 Student's t-tests, one for each game condition, will be performed to get the p-value and see if we can reject the null hypothesis.

In [27]:
# Import the necessary package
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# Get a dataframe that only holds data for games on the Neo Geo AES
neo_geo_data = data[data['console-name'] == 'Neo Geo AES']

# Run the t-test for loose games
stat, p = ttest_ind(neo_geo_data['loose-price'], data['loose-price'])
print(p)

# Run the t-test for complete-in-box games
stat, p = ttest_ind(neo_geo_data['cib-price'], data['cib-price'])
print(p)

# Run the t-test for new games
stat, p = ttest_ind(neo_geo_data['new-price'], data['new-price'])
print(p)

5.883105767623169e-150
1.7902653252334758e-131
2.3297966331472652e-73

All 3 p-values are exceptionally small, meaning we can reject the null hypothesis for each condition. That means that we have statistically significant evidence that Neo Geo AES titles are valued differently than the average game.

Now, I'll try to make the model I discussed at the beginning of this notebook.

Machine learning¶

The exact goal here will be creating a model that can ideally output the age at which the game should be priced at an inputted value given genre. I will be focusing on the complete-in-box prices as that is how I personally collect games, generally opening them and playing them but keeping all the components together and in good condition.

For example, say I want to buy a Xenoblade Chronicles 3, an upcoming RPG, for $40 complete-in-box. By inputting its genre and my desired price, I hope that my model will be able to output the age at which that game will be available for that price. I will be making a linear model due to its simplicity with regards to implementation and testing, and using interaction terms to account for genre's impact despite genre not having a numerical representation.

In [28]:
# Import the necessary packages
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression 
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Use get dummies to encode genre numerically, and add that encoding to the features used for prediction
genre_feature = pd.get_dummies(data['genre'], drop_first=True, prefix = "genre")
standard_features = data[['cib-price', 'genre']]
comb_feat = pd.concat([standard_features, genre_feature], axis=1)

# Get a list of genres
genres = list(set(data.genre.values))

# Get a value for the interaction between cib-price and genre
for s in filter(lambda s : s != 'Action ', genres):
    comb_feat["cib-price*" + s] = comb_feat["genre_" + s]*comb_feat["cib-price"]
    
# Get the x and y used for prediction
x = comb_feat.drop('genre', axis = 1)
y = np.array(data['age']).reshape(-1, 1)

# Split the data into training sets containing 80% of the data and testing sets containing 20% of the data
x_train, x_test, y_train,y_test = train_test_split(x,y,test_size =0.2)

# Fit the model on the training set and print a representation of its accuracy on the testing set, the coefficient of determination.
lm = LinearRegression()
lm.fit(x_train, y_train)
lm.score(x_test,y_test)
Out[28]:
0.054699264257643265

This coefficient of determination of exceptionally low, my model is supposedly accurate less than 10% of the time. Therefore, I should not be using it if I want accurate predictions.

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, it seems that the video game market is quite hard to predict. In retrospect, it's easy to prove that certain consoles or genres hold games of greater value, though extrapolating that data has lead to mixed results at best.

No strong correlations were found, and no accurate model was able to be created. It seems that genre has no consistent effect on price trends.

In the future, adding to this dataset with data relevant to individual game sales and console sales would be interesting. Perhaps also adding the publisher of a game would be useful. Based on my experience collecting, I suspect some correlations would be found there. With these extra features, perhaps a stronger model could be generated. As it is now, we can only conclude that our current dataset wasn't enough to make solid conclusions.
